22:36
The good news is I've cracked happiness. It's FOUR THINGS. (!) I'll start by saying that I think seeking happiness through chasing pleasures is terrible route! In psychology they talk about the Hedonistic Treadmill - where pleasures wear off over time and we need to keep increasing the thrill level. I.e. you can't really be happy through chasing material goods or drugs, or fancy food, or sex or all that. An ABSENCE of pleasures can make you unhappy - but seeking happiness FROM these things goes nowhere. Similar to you, I feel quite deeply happy I think. I can be down from time to time when under some pressure or if something I care about isn't workout out the way I want - but I tend to return to a general feeling of happiness and general positive overall feeling. When I think about *why* - of course I'm not really really sure - but here we go anyway...
22:36
👨‍🏫
22:38
THING 1 I feel thankful for the many great things I have in my life. Thankful for things like living very close to my work and not having to commute. Thankful that I have access to music and books and films (and documentaries! 😇) and stuff like that. I've been dabbling in meditation and they talk about being thankful - I feel really thankful for what I have - even with all my problems - because I know overall I'm luckier than the vast majority of humans who ever lived. I know that's a weird way to think about it, but a vanishingly small number of people who have ever been born have had electricity, clean running water, enough money to basically live without hardship, etc etc - INDOOR PLUMBING! 💩 So many great things. I must be in the luckiest 1% of all humans who ever lived. Even when my life is rubbish in some way or at some time. I'm still lucky.
22:39
Rather than comparing ourselves to others who have more and feeling jealous - instead trying to take a moment to feel thankful, and to reflect on the positive things we have can help us find happiness - even when some things are not so good. I've had moments of jealousy in my life. It's not good for the soul. So I think that helps me feel happy - to appreciate the luck I do have - and I really do feel so lucky. The richest man in the world a hundred years ago wasn't able to travel to as many countries as I have. In the next few weeks I am visiting an old friend in America and meeting a new friend in Venice (👋💃). That's amazing! Who gets to do that in their life? So reflecting on and really being aware of the good things in life - that's one of the things I think is important to feel happy.
22:39
THING 2 I also think feeling that people care about you and likewise, caring about other people helps us be happy. I have many friendly acquaintances - and that actually fills most of my social life - but I have a very small number of real close friends / family who I love very much, and who I admire and respect. I don't always see them very often - we have all moved to various cities and countries but I feel connected to them and they have wonderful souls and I feel honoured to be their friend. So I think that having people in your life who care for you and who you care for is another thing that I think makes people (and me!) happy.
22:39
THING 3 I think that having autonomy in life is also key to being happy. What that *exactly* means, I'm not sure. But being able to make decisions, think about solving problems, applying yourself to a task in the way that you feel is appropriate - I think that can be deeply satisfying and whilst it's not exactly the same thing as happiness, I think it's a key to living well - if you can be so lucky, to try to find an occupation that affords you this luxury. I've been offered three times my current salary to take a job in industry - but for a company I don't admire, and with way way less freedom than I currently experience - a big reason I am in academia is that I get to pursue work that I want to. These projects I mention - the climate game, the health game etc - this is me chasing what I want to chase - it's deeply satisfying and gives me happiness to be able to have control over what I do.
22:40
THING 4 And related to the autonomy idea - the last big thought I have on happiness (I think!) - I don't recall the Zizec line that you mentioned. But I do recall him suggesting that pursuing individual happiness is NOT the route to happiness - that it misses the point, and that we should be pursuing something greater. I think this hits the nail on the head. I think we need purpose. If we can use our autonomy to work towards something (and it might be ANYTHING) we think is important - I think that's key to long long term happiness. People get purpose from religion. From raising a family. From working on community projects. From all sorts of things. I think we need it. You're an atheist - I'm an atheist. We can't simply trick ourselves into thinking we get meaning by pleasing god. We have to find meaning ourselves. Working to some greater purpose - believing in it deeply - I think that can be a great fuel for happiness.
22:40
I don't believe any of my work is going to solve the world's problems at all. But I believe in trying and failing with clear eyes and an open heart. I believe in making a contribution. There are many things I do that don't give me meaning but that I enjoy. I love doing any form of game design - I enjoy the moment of 'being clever' and solving a design problem - and maybe that kind of competent, creative autonomy would be enough to keep me happy - I may go back for a few years to industry just for a change - but I think I'd always end up back chasing problems I think we need to solve - the few things I work on (like the climate game and like the health game) that DO connect to some higher purpose - that's the stuff that fills me up :D
22:41
Have you read the book Cloud Atlas? (or perhaps seen the movie?) It has a line in it that I love - “My life amounts to no more than one drop in a limitless ocean. Yet what is any ocean, but a multitude of drops?” That's the good stuff - Thaaaaaaaaat's the good stuff. 🤘
22:41
So to summarise my thesis! 👨‍🏫 I think happiness is: 1: Reflecting on what we have as opposed to being envious of what others have. 2: Being connected to people we care about. 3: Having a sufficient level of autonomy in our lives that we can pursue things we want, or pursue things in our own *way*. 4: Working towards some greater purpose.
